Lab - Linear regression¶

In this lab, you need to work with Students data and grades as labels for Portugese students. Your task is to fit a Linear model, and predict the grades (G3) based on suitable input variables. You are required to do the data manipulation (converting text to numeric), train-test splits etc to create the model.

Data is availabe in : https://raw.githubusercontent.com/colaberry/DSin100days/master/data/student-por.csv

Description is available here : https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance#

Once we do that, we need to first encode all the categorical variables to one hot encoded variables? Why are we doing this? We cannot build a regression model with categorical variables as the input. In regression, the outputs are continuous, where categorical variables are discrete. Pandas gives us an easy way of doing this.

Note, you could also use sklearn's sklearn.preprocessing.LabelEncoder followed by sklearn.preprocessing.OneHotEncoder to acheieve the same thing. In some scenarios that might be preferable. However, for this dataset we will stick with get_dummies from pandas. Read up the documentation and fill the code below.

Once you have the correlation matrix, we want to detect which pair of features have high correlations. For this purpose, we have first reset the index. You will have to implement pd.melt function where you will unpivot the new_corr matrix. The pd.melt function takes the new_corr matrix as an input. You will also need to provide the "index" as as id_vars to get "corr_pairs".

Once you have this information you will need to search for correlation values between between 0.6 and 0.999. You can use the series.between function for this. Remember that corr_pairs['value'] is a series object and for a series object you can use the between(val1, val2) to identify the rows where the values between va1l and val2 are present.
